stage III prediction on CODEX data¶

The goal of this notebook is to find which molecules are good predictors of stage III among the cytokine panels collected on the CSF and plasma samples.

In [1]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd

1. reading the data ¶

In [3]:
## first, grabbing molecule names from the original files (this is a bit dirty...)

df =pd.read_csv('data/Inflammation_Plasma_Etter.csv',sep=';', skiprows=[0,1,2,4,5,6] , index_col=0)
df.drop(columns=['Plate ID' , 'QC Warning'] , inplace=True)

inflammatoryMolecules = list( df.columns )

df =pd.read_csv('data/Neurology_Plasma_Etter.csv',sep=';', skiprows=[0,1,2,4,5,6] , index_col=0)
df.drop(columns=['Plate ID' , 'QC Warning'] , inplace=True)

neuroMolecules = list( df.columns )

## removing common molecules. we keep the ones in neuro
inter = set( inflammatoryMolecules ).intersection(neuroMolecules)
for c in inter:
    inflammatoryMolecules.remove(c)

2. using ROC - AUC to get the drivers behind the response ¶

2.1 I vs. III ¶

In [8]:
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc


M = df_metadata.index[ ( df_metadata.stageGroup == "I") | (df_metadata.stageGroup == "III") ]

data = df_molecular.loc[ M , : ]
grouping = df_metadata.loc[ M , 'stageGroup']
In [9]:
data.shape
Out[9]:
(33, 364)
In [10]:
fpr = {}
tpr = {}
roc_auc = {}
missing = {}
for col in data.columns:
    
    nullMask = data[col].isnull()
    
    G = grouping[~nullMask]
    D = data.loc[~nullMask,col]
    
    
    
    fpr_loc, tpr_loc, _ = roc_curve(G, D , pos_label = 'III')
    roc_auc_loc = auc(fpr_loc, tpr_loc)
    

    if roc_auc_loc>0.5:
        fpr[col], tpr[col] , roc_auc[col] = fpr_loc, tpr_loc , roc_auc_loc
        missing[col] = nullMask.sum()
    else: #then it is better to use the opposite of the value to predict response        
        lbl = '-('+col+')'
        fpr[lbl], tpr[lbl], _ = roc_curve(G, -D , pos_label = 'III')
        roc_auc[lbl] = auc(fpr[lbl], tpr[lbl])
        missing[lbl] = nullMask.sum()
In [11]:
sortedMolecules = sorted( roc_auc.items(), key = lambda x : x[1] , reverse=True)

fig,axes = plt.subplots(3,3 , figsize = (14,14))



for i, x in enumerate( sortedMolecules[:9] ):
    
    molec, roc_v = x
    
    ax = axes[ i%3 , i//3 ]
    
    print(molec, roc_v)
    plt.figure()
    lw = 2
    ax.plot(fpr[molec], tpr[molec], color='darkorange',
             lw=lw, label='ROC curve (area = %0.2f)' % roc_auc[molec])
    ax.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=lw, linestyle='--')
    ax.set_xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    ax.set_ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    ax.set_xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    ax.set_ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    ax.set_title('ROC : {} - fraction missing:{:.3f}'.format(molec, missing[molec]/data.shape[0]))
    ax.legend(loc="lower right")
fig.suptitle('I vs. III - ROC AUC top 9 molecules ', fontsize=16)
fig.tight_layout(pad=2.0)
fig.savefig( "images/I_III.ROC.pdf" )

'roc_auc' : [ roc_auc[k[0]] for k in sortedMolecules ],
'fraction_missing' : [ missing[k[0]] for k in sortedMolecules ]})

2.3 I and II vs. III ¶

This is the most clinically relevant experiment

In [16]:
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc


M = df_metadata.index[ ( df_metadata.stageGroup == "I") | ( df_metadata.stageGroup == "II") | (df_metadata.stageGroup == "III") ]

data = df_molecular.loc[ M , : ]
grouping = df_metadata.loc[ M , 'stageGroup'].copy()
grouping[grouping=='I'] = "I/II"
grouping[grouping=='II'] = "I/II"
grouping.value_counts()
Out[16]:
I/II    25
III     15
Name: stageGroup, dtype: int64

3. random forest ¶

In [10]:
%%time
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.model_selection import LeaveOneOut
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, balanced_accuracy_score
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline

N = data.shape[0]

##### Now we use RandomForestClassifier
grid_values = [{'RF__criterion': ['entropy','gini'],
               'RF__n_estimators':np.arange(1,500,100), 
               'RF__max_depth':np.arange(2,int(np.ceil(N/10)),20),
               'RF__min_samples_split':np.arange(2,int(np.ceil(N/10)),20),
              'RF__min_samples_leaf':np.arange(1,int(np.ceil(N/10)),20),
              'RF__max_features':['sqrt','log2',None]}]


pipe = Pipeline([("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy="mean")) , 
                ('RF',RandomForestClassifier(class_weight='balanced'))])
grid_tree_acc = GridSearchCV(pipe, 
                             param_grid = grid_values, 
                             cv = LeaveOneOut(),
                             scoring='balanced_accuracy',n_jobs=-1)


grid_tree_acc.fit(data, grouping)


print('Grid best parameter (max. balanced_accuracy): ', grid_tree_acc.best_params_)
print('Grid best score (balanced_accuracy): ', grid_tree_acc.best_score_)

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
y_pred=grid_tree_acc.predict(data)

confusion_mc_c = confusion_matrix(grouping, y_pred)
df_cm_c = pd.DataFrame(confusion_mc_c, 
                     index = ["I/II","III"], columns = ["I/II","III"])

plt.figure(figsize=(5.5,4))
sns.heatmap(df_cm_c, annot=True)
plt.title(
    'crit: {} - max_depth: {} - min_split: {} - min_leaf: {}\nAccuracy:{:.3f}'.format(
        grid_tree_acc.best_params_['RF__criterion'],
        grid_tree_acc.best_params_['RF__max_depth'],
        grid_tree_acc.best_params_['RF__min_samples_split'],
        grid_tree_acc.best_params_['RF__min_samples_leaf'],
        balanced_accuracy_score(grouping, y_pred) ) )

w=grid_tree_acc.best_estimator_['RF'].feature_importances_#get the weights

featureW = pd.DataFrame( {'feature': data.columns,'weight':w} )

# sort them by absolute value
featureWsorted = featureW.sort_values(by=['weight'] , 
                                      ascending=False , 
                                      key=lambda col : col.abs())

bestUnion = set(bestAUC).union(bestRF)
bestUnion



## label repelling from : https://python-graph-gallery.com/web-text-repel-with-matplotlib
from adjustText import adjust_text
fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,10))

ax.scatter(dfAUC['importanceRF'] , dfAUC['roc_auc'] )
ax.set_xlabel("random forest importance score", fontsize = 26 , fontname = 'Arial')
ax.set_ylabel("ROC-AUC", fontsize = 26 , fontname = 'Arial')

TEXTS = []
for m in bestUnion:
    
    TEXTS.append( ax.text( x=dfAUC.loc[m,'importanceRF'],
                          y=dfAUC.loc[m,'roc_auc'], 
                          fontname = 'Arial', fontsize=16,
                          s=m) )

    
adjust_text(TEXTS, 
            expand_points=(1.2, 1.1), expand_text=(1.1,1.2),
            arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="->", color="#7F7F7F", lw=1),
            ax=ax)
fig.savefig("images/classI+II_vs_III_prediction_ROCAUC_RFimportance.pdf")

conclusion/Methods: ¶

We have trained a random forest to predict the patient class (I/II , or III) from all cytokine samples. We used leave-one-out cross-validation to optimize hyper-parameters and optimized a balanced accuracy metric. We then compare the ROC-AUC score of indicvidual molecules with their importance in the random forest.

Back to ToC

4. Random forest, Plasma only ¶

let's perform the same analysis on plasma sample only.

In [18]:
M = df_metadata.index[ ( df_metadata.stageGroup == "I") | ( df_metadata.stageGroup == "II") | (df_metadata.stageGroup == "III") ]
dataPlasma = df_molecular.loc[ M , [ c for c in df_molecular.columns if c.startswith("Plasma")] ]
In [19]:
dataPlasma.shape
Out[19]:
(40, 182)
In [20]:
%%time
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.model_selection import LeaveOneOut
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, balanced_accuracy_score
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline

N = data.shape[0]

##### Now we use RandomForestClassifier
grid_values = [{'RF__criterion': ['entropy','gini'],
               'RF__n_estimators':np.arange(1,200,10), 
               'RF__max_depth':np.arange(2,int(np.ceil(N/10)),20),
               'RF__min_samples_split':np.arange(2,int(np.ceil(N/10)),20),
              'RF__min_samples_leaf':np.arange(1,int(np.ceil(N/10)),20),
              'RF__max_features':['sqrt','log2',None]}]


pipe = Pipeline([("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy="mean")) , 
                ('RF',RandomForestClassifier(class_weight='balanced'))])
grid_tree_acc_plasma = GridSearchCV(pipe, 
                             param_grid = grid_values, 
                             cv = LeaveOneOut(),
                             scoring='balanced_accuracy',n_jobs=-1)


grid_tree_acc_plasma.fit(dataPlasma, grouping)


print('Grid best parameter (max. balanced_accuracy): ', grid_tree_acc_plasma.best_params_)
print('Grid best score (balanced_accuracy): ', grid_tree_acc_plasma.best_score_)

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
y_pred=grid_tree_acc_plasma.predict(dataPlasma)

confusion_mc_c = confusion_matrix(grouping, y_pred)
df_cm_c = pd.DataFrame(confusion_mc_c, 
                     index = ["I/II","III"], columns = ["I/II","III"])

plt.figure(figsize=(5.5,4))
sns.heatmap(df_cm_c, annot=True)
plt.title(
    'crit: {} - max_depth: {} - min_split: {} - min_leaf: {}\nAccuracy:{:.3f}'.format(
        grid_tree_acc_plasma.best_params_['RF__criterion'],
        grid_tree_acc_plasma.best_params_['RF__max_depth'],
        grid_tree_acc_plasma.best_params_['RF__min_samples_split'],
        grid_tree_acc_plasma.best_params_['RF__min_samples_leaf'],
        balanced_accuracy_score(grouping, y_pred) ) )

plt.ylabel('True label')
plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

In [22]:
w=grid_tree_acc_plasma.best_estimator_['RF'].feature_importances_#get the weights

featureW = pd.DataFrame( {'feature': dataPlasma.columns,'weight':w} )

# sort them by absolute value
featureWsorted = featureW.sort_values(by=['weight'] , 
                                      ascending=False , 
                                      key=lambda col : col.abs())

# get the non-null ones
print('Features sorted per importance:')
featureWsorted.index = featureWsorted.feature
featureWsorted.iloc[ range(10) ]

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
In [51]:
## label repelling from : https://python-graph-gallery.com/web-text-repel-with-matplotlib
from adjustText import adjust_text

bestAUC = dfAUC_plasma['roc_auc'].sort_values(ascending=False)[:10].index
bestRF = dfAUC_plasma['importanceRF'].sort_values(ascending=False)[:10].index
bestUnion = set(bestAUC).union(bestRF)

fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,10))

ax.scatter(dfAUC_plasma['importanceRF'] , dfAUC_plasma['roc_auc'] )
ax.set_xlabel("random forest importance score", fontsize = 26 , fontname = 'Arial')
ax.set_ylabel("ROC-AUC", fontsize = 26 , fontname = 'Arial')

TEXTS = []
for m in bestUnion:
    
    TEXTS.append( ax.text( x=dfAUC_plasma.loc[m,'importanceRF'],
                          y=dfAUC_plasma.loc[m,'roc_auc'], 
                          fontname = 'Arial', fontsize=16,
                          s=m.partition('_')[2]) )

ax.text( x=dfAUC_plasma['importanceRF'].max(),
         y=dfAUC_plasma['roc_auc'].min(), 
         fontname = 'Arial', color='#7F7F7F', fontsize=26,
         ha='right',
         va='bottom',
         s='Plasma measurements only') 

    
adjust_text(TEXTS, 
            expand_points=(1.2, 1.1), expand_text=(1.1,1.5),
            arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="->", color="#7F7F7F", lw=1),
            ax=ax)
fig.savefig("images/classI+II_vs_III_prediction_ROCAUC_RFimportance_plasmaOnly.pdf")
fig.savefig("images/classI+II_vs_III_prediction_ROCAUC_RFimportance_plasmaOnly.png")
